## Project context
Read CLAUDE.md for full project context, design direction, and architecture decisions.

## Component creation rules
- New components go in `src/components/new/` until the old design is fully replaced.
- Every component must pull content from `src/data/portfolio.ts` — never hardcode text, dates, descriptions, or tech stacks directly in JSX.
- Use `"use client"` directive for components that need Framer Motion or browser APIs.
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling. No CSS modules, no styled-components, no MUI.

## Animation rules
- Use Framer Motion (`motion` package, already installed) for entrance animations and hover effects.
- For always-running background animations inside project/experience cards (e.g., orbiting satellite, racing car), use CSS `@keyframes` in globals.css or inline styles — Framer Motion is overkill for these.
- Every project card in the bento grid must have a unique visual animation that represents the project.
- Every experience card should have a subtle background animation representing the work.

## Styling rules
- Font: Sora for headings and body text, JetBrains Mono for code/tech labels.
- Dark theme: background #050505, text #f0f0f0, muted text #666-#888.
- Accent gradient: blue (#60a5fa) → indigo (#818cf8) → purple (#c084fc) → pink (#f472b6).
- Cards: background #0a0a0a, border #151515, hover border #2a2a2a.
- Use numbered section headers (01 Experience, 02 Projects, etc.) with a horizontal line.

## Commit rules
- One logical change per commit.
- Commit message format: imperative mood, concise (e.g., "Add Hero component with floating orbs animation").
- Never commit broken code — `npm run dev` must work after every commit.
- Run `npm run lint` before pushing.

## What NOT to do
- Don't use ClashDisplay font (shared template with friend's portfolio).
- Don't use the floating pill-style navbar (shared template element).
- Don't use the vertical timeline for experience (shared template element).
- Don't use MUI components or Three.js (removing these dependencies).
- Don't put DARC or NASA in the projects section — they are experiences.
